[5] Philippines
Date: 28 Feb 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Bayanihan.org - Philippines [edited]
<http://www.bayanihan.org/html/article.php/20070228125737119>

The Department of Health (DOH) has already declared a year-round
campaign against the dreaded dengue fever, but cases, including
deaths, continue to climb. A DOH report showed that since 1 Jan to 26
Feb this year [2007], a total of 1579 dengue cases with 7 deaths were
recorded from all over the country.
The figure was 272 cases higher than the reported cases compared to
the department's previous report ending 13 Feb 2007. The number of
deaths also went up to 7, or an additional one death. However, the
DOH report showed that the dengue reported during the period is lower
than that of the same period in 2006, which was 3348 cases with 51 deaths.
The DOH report also showed the clustering of dengue cases, or 3 or
more cases, in a barangay [larger political-geographic subdivision
within a city] during the past 4 weeks in barangays Potrero and
Tonsuya in Malabon; Davao City; Bagua and Rosary Heights 8 in
Cotabato and in Poblacion in Bayuga, Agusan del Sur.
From a seasonal disease that breaks out only during the rainy
season, dengue fever has become a year-round disease. As early as
January [2007], epidemics of dengue were declared in Agusan del Sur
and in San Pedro, Laguna.
With the recent development, the DOH correspondingly launched an
all-out and year-round campaign against dengue that is aggressively
being undertaken in the barangay level and with the assistance of the
local government units. Health Secretary Francisco Duque III earlier
said that the heightened awareness of dengue and community
participation would determine the success or failure of the battle
against the disease. Duque reminded the public that the only means to
fight dengue is to search out and destroy the breeding sites of
_Aedes aegypti_, the dengue-causing mosquitoes, and seek medical help
when early signs such as fever and rashes set in.
--
